<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
    <head>
        <meta charset="utf-8">
        <title>rsstodolist: an RSS based todo-list</title>
        <meta name="robots" content="<%= public ? 'index,follow' : 'noindex,nofollow' %>"/>
        <meta name="keywords" content="rss todolist, todolist"/>
        <meta name="author" content="Gr&eacute;gory Paul"/>
        <meta name="description" content="An RSS based todo-list"/>
        <style type="text/css">
            body { margin: 0; background-color: #3B7CC0; font-family: sans-serif; }
            #content { padding: 2%; background-color: white; border-right: 3px solid #159EFE; border-left: 3px solid #159EFE; }
            h1 { color: #159EFE; }
            h2 { color: #63ADF5; margin: 1em 0.5em 1em 0.5em; }
            h3 { color: #3B7CC0; margin-left: 0.5em; }
            ul { list-style-type: square; }
            input { margin: .25em; }
            input[type=submit] { margin: .5em  0; }
            code { display: block; margin: 0.5em 0; word-break: break-all; }
            @media (min-width:1024px) {
                p { margin-left: 4em; }
                body { margin: 0 5%;  }
                input[name=url] { width: 90%; }
                ul { margin-left: 3em; }
                h3 { margin-left: 2.5em; }
            }
        </style>
        <link rel="icon" type="image/png" href="./static/favicon.png" />
        <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, minimum-scale=1.0, maximum-scale=1.0, initial-scale=1.0, user-scalable=no" />
    </head>
    <body>
        <div id="content">
            <h1>üìÉ rsstodolist</h1>

            <p>rsstodolist is an URL oriented to-read-list based on an RSS XML feed. Typical use case is to save web pages to read later on a RSS feed.</p>

            <% if (public) { %>

            <h2>‚ö†Ô∏è Service migration</h2>
            <p>Service has been migrated from heroku to fly.io. Data hasn't been migrated so your feeds have been truncated. 
                Contact me if you need to restore some of them.</p>

            <h2>üíª Self-hosting for more privacy &amp; reliability</h2>
            <p>That service is public and ¬´ open ¬ª, meaning anyone knowing your feed name may see your items, add or remove them.</p>
            <p>Also, that service is hosted via hobby plan on fly.io with some limitations.</p>
            <p>So, for more reliability and privacy, I <strong>strongly</strong> suggest you to self-host that application (see <a href="#related">related projects below</a>).</p>

            <% } else { %>

            <h2>Feeds list</h2>
            <p>You can see all feeds on <a href="./list">feeds list</a>.</p>

            <% } %>

            <h2>‚ûï Add an URL to your feed</h2>

            <h3>1. By using that form :</h3>
            <form method="get" action="add">
                <p>
                    <label for="url">URL</label>&nbsp;:&nbsp;<input type="url" id="url" name="url" placeholder="https://fr.wikipedia.org/"/><br/>
                    <label for="name">Feed name</label>&nbsp;:&nbsp;<input type="text" id="name" name="name" placeholder="somename"/><br/>
                    <input type="submit" />
                </p>
            </form>
            <h3>2. By calling an URL :</h3>
            <p><a href="add?name=somename&amp;url=https://fr.wikipedia.org/" rel="nofollow"><%= rootUrl %>/add?name=somename&amp;url=https://fr.wikipedia.org/</a></p>
            <ul>
                <li>By default, the feed title will be fetched from the web page title. You may force it by using the &quot;&amp;title&quot; parameter.</li>
                <li>Also, by default, your feed will contain 25 items. You can change that by setting &quot;&amp;limit&quot; parameter from 1 to 500.</li>
                <li>A description for the link may be added by using the &quot;description&quot; parameter</li>
                <li>You may also use short parameters like &quot;n&quot; for &quot;name&quot;, &quot;u&quot; for &quot;url&quot;, &quot;t&quot; for &quot;title&quot;, &quot;l&quot; for &quot;limit&quot; or &quot;d&quot; for &quot;description&quot; like that : <a href="add?n=somename&amp;u=https://fr.wikipedia.org/" rel="nofollow"><%= rootUrl %>/add?n=somename&amp;u=https://fr.wikipedia.org/</a></li>
            </ul>

            <h3>3. By using that <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bookmarklet" title="Learn more about bookmarklet on Wikipedia">bookmarklet</a> :</h3>
            <p>Create a new bookmarklet and paste the following code in the URL field :
            <code>javascript:var rss=prompt('RSS feed name ?');var r=new XMLHttpRequest();r.open('GET','<%= rootUrl %>/add?n='+rss+'&amp;url='+encodeURIComponent(window.location),true);r.setRequestHeader('Content-Type','text/plain;charset=UTF-8');r.onreadystatechange=function(){if(r.readyState==4){alert("Request sent : "+(r.status===200)+" ("+r.status+")");}};r.send(null);</code>
            Then, clicking on that bookmark will add current page to the RSS feed.
            </p>

            <h3>4. By using an extension :</h3>
            <p>A <a href="https://addons.mozilla.org/fr/firefox/addon/rsstodolist/">Firefox addon</a> and <a href="https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/rsstodolist/gjnfedompndjcoeannmcppbckbkjhpkd">Chrome extension</a> are available. It will use public instance by default but you can configure your self-host instance in options.</p>

            <h2>üìÉ Get your feed :</h2>
            <p><a href="?name=somename" rel="nofollow"><%= rootUrl %>/?name=somename</a> or <a href="?n=somename" rel="nofollow"><%= rootUrl %>/?n=somename</a></p>

            <h2>‚ûñ Remove an URL from your feed</h2>
            <h3>By calling an URL :</h3>
            <p><a href="del?name=somename&amp;url=https://fr.wikipedia.org/" rel="nofollow"><%= rootUrl %>/del?name=somename&amp;url=https://fr.wikipedia.org/</a></p>

            <h2>‚ùì Feedback</h2>
            <p>Please contact me via <a href="https://paulgreg.me/">paulgreg.me</a>.</p>

